<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911223-0099</DOCNO><DOCID>911223-0099.</DOCID><HL>   International:   China May Be Able to Get   U.S. Missile Technology</HL><DATE>12/23/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>TRADE ISSUES (TRD)</NS><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)</GV><RE>CHINA (CH)FAR EAST (FE)IRAN (IR)MIDDLE EAST (ML)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PAKISTAN (PK)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)SYRIA (SY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Bush administration said it will liftrestrictions on the export of missile technology to Chinaonce Beijing formally agrees to adopt safeguards againstmissile proliferation.   In a letter to Sen. Jesse Helms (R., N.C.), rankingminority member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, aState Department official said China has agreed that itssales of missiles to Syria, Pakistan and Iran should conformto guidelines in the so-called Missile Technology ControlRegime. Nations that sign the control regime pledge theywon't sell missiles with a range of more than 300 kilometers(about 180 miles) and a warhead size exceeding 500 kilograms(1,100 pounds).</LP><TEXT>   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said that whenChina formally adopts missile-control limits, the U.S. willlift controls on sales of missile technology to China.   A State Department official said the U.S. hasn't yetdecided whether to lift a ban on the launching of U.S.-madesatellites by Chinese rockets, imposed after the Chinesegovernment's violent 1989 routing of pro-democracydemonstrators from Tiananmen Square.</TEXT></DOC>